data.name: label6.Text
data.value: Swelling of all or part of a breast (even if no lump is felt) Skin dimpling (sometimes looking like an orange peel) Breast or nipple pain Nipple retraction (turning inward) Nipple or breast skin that is red, dry, flaking, or thickened Nipple discharge (other than breast milk) Swollen lymph nodes under the arm or near the collar bone

data.name: label7.Text
data.value: This program was developed by four ADA University students: Asiman Mammadzada, Minura Hajisoy, Rumiyya Alili and Narmina Mahmudova as a part of their research topic. The aim of the program is to connect healthcare and technology as doctors are facing difficulties working with image data as well as contribute to the early detection of breast cancer and empower women who are going through recovery process.

data.name: label8.Text
data.value: Maintain a healthy weight Be physically active (try to exercise at least 30 minutes a day) Avoid alcohol or consume in moderation Breastfeed your children, if possible If you are taking hormone replacement therapy or oral contraceptives, ask your doctor about the risks to determine if they are right for you If you have a family history of breast cancer, inherited changes to your BRCA1 and BRCA2 genes or have a precancerous breast condition, talk to your doctor about ways to lower your risk
